I have been struggling so much with generational and cultural conflict. I become so jealous seeing all of my friends' relationships with their parents, because my own have never supported me in any aspect of my life, despite any success I have attained. Whether it be career-oriented, romantically, personally, about my friends, my decisions-- anything ever, I am never supported. I do not want to be who they want me to be. I have my own dreams. Please, please, do not take a supportive family unit for granted. There is not a single day in my life that I do not wish for my familial barriers to erode, for them to accept me for who I am and what I love. I am tired of having parents with archaic mentalities, and I cannot stand to have their expectations thrust onto me. I am constantly shadowboxing with my future, ricocheting between my secret life of who I really am and my mundane projected self unto my parents. I want to live my own life without ruining the ones I love most. If you have that luxury, please, please cherish it.

I try to live my life in such a way that I don't fall into behavioral paradigms that hurt others, perpetuate stereotypes, and make life harder for people. I'm usually pretty good at this, I think.
Sexism, sexual stigmas, and misandry/misogyny are the issues that seem to affect my friends of all races, classes, and orientations most on a daily basis. That means that in order to affect the most positive change for the people I care about most, I should focus my behavior on challenging these particular problems.

I'm increasingly coming to understand that putting the burden of approach in the (heterosexual) dating world on men is a really fucking huge problem, and that if I want to live my life in a way I respect, saying "yes" to people I'm not initially attracted to isn't enough. I have to stop waiting for guys to approach me and start asking them out myself.

BUT: this presupposes that I'm attracted enough to a guy to ask them out or initiate a hookup. And that happens so rarely as to be negligible. So what should I do? Just ask out people I'm not attracted to? That just seems like oscillating along an Aristotelian mean virtue spectrum, and those never work right anyway.

Dear Stanford undergraduates who are feeling upset and confused about why they are here, if they deserve to be here, etc.: please read the following article about the undergraduate admissions process.

The Stanford undergraduate admissions office now employs a staff of 52 people, and your application is only guaranteed one read (if you're a legacy, you are guaranteed two reads).  69 percent of Stanford's applicants over the past five years with SATs of 2400the highest score possibledidn't get in.

Thank you.

I told you that I would write you poetry.  I don't know if you believed me!

I don't know you well enough to say what sort of a person you are.  We've barely talked, yet we smile at each other:
I don't know if that fact is beautiful, but I suspect so.
I told you the first time we met that you were the image of grace!  
I stand by this!
Who could be so egoistic as to write poetry to you?  You are poetry!  
Your smile!  Who doesn't get feel a little envious of Richard Powers every time you smile up at him!
You--certainly, the image of beauty.  No one can match your face, your form, your movements, your smile.
But I don't know how much it means, after all.  
I don't know where you came from, or where you hope to go, 
or who your mother is, or what sort of burden you carry, 
Or why you dance, or what you think of yourself,
Or what it is like to be a beautiful woman in this world!!
I said once that you might be a personification of the moon.  I don't know why I feel this way.  
But I see you more often than her, which in the end is a great pity.
---

I am sure of this because everyone seems to turn out to be.

I think I will put a moratorium on the search for love until I can be sure that I can write poetry 
for people who aren't physical incarnations of heavenly bodies.

"From wikipedia: ""Affirmative action or positive discrimination[1] (known as employment equity in Canada, and positive action in the UK) is the policy of providing special opportunities for, and ****favoring members of****, a disadvantaged group""

The thing I hate most about affirmative action is the idiotic, oversimplifying assumption that if you're black (substitute your favorite minority in the rest of this post. Using black for simplicity.) your life was hard, and if you're white (substitute your favorite evil majority in the rest of this post. Using white for simplicity.), your life was easy.

Basically, if you're a low-income white, fuck you. Your application is probably not as impressive as the super-rich white's, given that your background did not give you as many opportunities. So, you lose against them. Then, when put against a minority, you lose, too, because your race is not as politically cool to accept (there're too many white people in power, am i rite?!!?!). If you ever speak out, youre a racist -- last year or so, there were some people trying to make a white-only scholarship for exactly these low-income men and women. They were shot down by various political groups as if they were the devil incarnate. The very few who do get in anyway are rightfully pissed, post on Stanford Confessions, and are shot down further.

Affirmative action is a naive, misguided effort that punishes the wrong people. The ones that are so popular to hate (super rich evil whites) will get in anyway. Even if they dont, they have enough money to live and oppress for years to come regardless of whether you give them a prestigious college diploma. As usual, the little guy loses because one of the big guys pissed someone off. 

So, why not judge everyone individually, with race never coming into play (i.e., dont discriminate based on race by using different application pools, etc.)? If someone has provably suffered some hardship in life (because of discrimination, disability, low income, whatever), then sure, boost their application; their accomplishments are all the more impressive if they were achieved in shitty conditions. But boost on a case by case basis, not because of what boxes they checked under race in their app. And yes, on average, this might result in boosting blacks applications more often than those of whites, this is perfectly fine. But doing so blindly, across the board, just to make sure there's a certain percentage of each race/sex, is political correctness bullshit. Its not fair in any reasonable sense of the word, and all it does is encourage people to victimize themselves (i.e., your college counselor tells you to check pacific islander rather than asian -- friends experience), even in cases where its doubtful whether thats actually true.
"

"In response to the recent angry posts from both sides:

If you get in because of affirmative action, you're under qualified by definition (i.e., you would not have gotten in solely because of your skills/qualifications). Whether that is good for society / fair is another debate, but don't pretend like the above is not true. With ALL ELSE EQUAL, you're more likely to get in if you're a minority. "Can we do away with Stanford Confessions? I'm about to unlike this page, but I feel like this needs to be said before I do. When I liked this page, I thought this would be a place that we could anonymously confess to our mini-crushes, various little truths we're not ready to admit out loud, and just to gather and listen to one another as we share a little bit about ourselves that we're not ready to say in person. Yet that's not what this page is. At all.

Stanford Confessions has turned into a page where insecure students at Stanford try to pull down other students. You guys want an affirmation that your major is better than other majors, that you deserve to be here more than some other people for whatever reason, and that you're an all-around amazing person while everyone else sucks. But I should just go ahead and tell you that writing this down on some anonymous form in hopes that someone reads it and feels inferior to you won't work. It will not make this any more true. 

Give it up. Embrace your insecurities. You are not better than anyone else. Look around, that girl in your math class? She's a genius. That guy you converse with in Spanish? He could run/swim a mile with you and overlap you twice. And that person on the floor above you will probably save the world once and twice. And yes, that frustrates you. You start reexamining your life and wonder if you'll ever match up. And you start struggling with admitting that everyone around you is freaking AWESOME in some way. So what do you do? You go to Stanford Confessions and try to make at least someone feel less awesome than you. But, just saying, that's not going to make them any less amazing, no matter how hard you try.

So I'm going to give you some advice. Try to focus on believing in yourself. Remember that you're here for a reason. There's something that makes you deserving of your acceptance to Stanford, because we all are. And one of the most beautiful things about getting to go to a school like Stanford is having the opportunity to interact with the freaking amazing people all around you.

So stop trying to pull others down to your level. Instead pull yourself up. Don't get insecure about the accomplishments and potential of everyone around you, get INSPIRED. Aspire to learn more, do more, and love yourself more. Then change your attitude and realize that we're all in this together. We're family. That's why we're able to write some very real confessions on this page. And know that if one of us does better, earns a Nobel Prize, becomes the next President of the United States, or wins an Olympic gold medal, we are ALL better for it. We're Stanford. Together. So yeah, continue to confess, But allow this to be a support system for others. Because in reality we ALL need each other to succeed. 

#CardinalLove

"

Step 1: Take your phone out of your backpack, stare at it with a confused look on your face.
Step 2: Stand up, phone in hand (by this time your professor is probably looking at you like WTF) but don't worry it is all part of the plan.
Step 3: Leave your backpack behind and walk out of the classroom without saying a word.
Step 4: Walk into the hallway outside of your class. Make certain your phone is off. Begin dramatizing how you would react if someone was on the other line giving you really really bad news ( someone has just died bad news). Make sure you speak up so that the class on the other side of the door can hear you.
Step 5: Burst back into the class room with a devastated look on your face. Grab your shit. Hand the professor the exam and tell him you have to go. ( The professor will know something is seriously wrong because he/she would have heard you outside the door in the hallway.)
Step 6: High tail it out of there. You have just walked out of your exam successfully.  
Step 7: Wait a couple of hours, then email the professor saying someone in your family just died and you are leaving Palo Alto now.
Step 8: Wait for the reply, which will 99.9% will be "" I understand, my deepest sympathies, please contact me when possible to reschedule the exam.""
Step 9: Email your other three professors, telling them what went down, how you left in the middle of your exam that morning, and If they have any questions or concerns to please contact the professor or the class you walked out of.

Until recently, I was madly in love with a girl from my class. She was extremely kind, caring, active, full of life, enthusiastic, and unbelievably beautiful. I was thinking about her day and night, and I loved her so much that I thought I would never fall in love with anybody else. Then after we started talking and knowing each other better, I felt that she started to like me, and my other friends who were with us told me the same thing. So, she started to find dumb excuses to spend more time with me. 

However, I knew that she was in a serious relationship with a great guy and they were having wonderful romance. When I felt that she liked me (which was becoming more and more obvious), I started to slowly push her away from me until we were hello, how are you? type of friends. I understand that shes a human and she has feelings and needs, but I also knew that she was making a big mistake. I did not ever want to be involved in cheating or destroying the guys life. I thought of how I might feel if some other guy did that to my girlfriend, and how much pain and sadness that could cause.

When I look back, this was one of the best decisions Ive made it my life. My heart wanted her more than anything else in life, but I came to learn that you shouldnt always follow your feelings and let them overtake you. You must evaluate the situation and future outcomes with a sound-mind. I learned self-disciple and self-control. This gave me a sense of power over my own mind and emotions. 

After a few months of terrible pain and torture, I managed to push away all the intense love feeling I had for her. As a result, she is still having an amazing relationship with the guy and they are both happy and in love with each other. As for me, I am happy that I was able to make her joyful and kept her away from ruining her relationship. I am glad that everything worked out smoothly, and we both could carry on with our lives.

The cost of everything (basic products, rent, gas, tuition) is rising faster than people's salaries, to the point where it's becoming difficult to survive and support families. I am an econ major, and with each passing day, I grow to hate my major, but I know it's worth it because it will provide me some decent job security. I was not born into a rich family, so I have a major that will make me money ASAP for me to support myself, because once my grants, scholarships, loans are gone when I graduate, my parents will have to go through financial hell just to make sure I live, unless I get a great career. "During the summer, I met a kid who belongs to a frat - which I wont say. Ill call him John. I dont usually hang out anyone from the Greek community, but this was my chance to put all the rumors I had heard to the test. So, I would go over to his house and we would engage in real conversations about each others lives. At first he seemed really nice. 

Over the course of a few weeks, I learned that he is obsessed with his image. I learned that he is just as insecure about his body as a 13-year-old girl. I learned that he is ashamed of his older sister for being a lesbian because he perceives her as weak. He had not spoken to her since she came out. What a loving and supportive brother. The funny thing is he didnt know I was bisexual.until I told immediately after that statement. I could see the embarrassment in his eyes. 

I met some of his brothers, one of which I cannot forget. Ill call him Alex. The conversation of alcohol limits came up. I knew that drinking was a staple of Greek culture, but as an intelligent, loving, caring, and independent human being, I asserted that ones health should come before a college social organization. John wouldnt have any of it. In a militant manner, he reprimanded Alex for his inability to handle his alcohol. He demanded that instead of limiting his drinks, Alex should increase his alcohol intake (to increase his tolerance) because his social standing in Greek life depends on it. The social standing of their house depends on it. After a heated discussion about alcohol and limits, John gets up to use the bathroom. 

A moment after John closed the door, Joe confessed: The reason I dont want to drink is because I become violent with girls. Ive been called a rapist by female hecklers because of what they heard. I have a hard time controlling myself when I drink a lot
..Does John know about this?..
Yeah..
Umthats not okay. I know what John thinks, but personally I think you should limit your alcohol. I dont think you should be drinking more; that would just make things worse. You need to care of yourself

The door handle stirs. 
We both look at each other. We say nothing, but we silently agree. 
I had an eerie feeling when John walked back into the room. He felt like an oppressive force. I could not understand why John, a brother, and alleged friend of Alexs, would completely disregard Alexs well being for the sake of his own image. Selfish. Manipulative. Cold. Repulsive. 
I felt sorry for both of them. Both John and Alex were victims of a flawed culture. I could not understand what the appeal was. I could not understand why they continue to uphold ridiculous values and allow the self-destruction of their friends and loved ones.

John and I did have casual sex. He was sweet, passionate, and gentle. However, I noticed a change in Johns character, night to day.
He came to my house for the first time. I was still in the process of moving in, but tried to make him comfortable. We were about to watch a show on Netflix when he said, You know, I dont like cuddling. I dont want to come over and do all this. I just want to come here, have sex, and leave. I want to be good at something. I mean, youre good at blowjobs. I want to be known for eating girls out like a champ. Summers about to end and we shouldnt see each other when school starts. I want to use this time to improve my skills.
Yes, this actually happened.
